a) Use of suitable and appropriate PPE: overalls, safety shoes, hard hat, gloves, lifejacket, etc.; 
b) Adequate lighting to be provided. Use portable lighting if necessary; 
c) Trip hazards and any overhead obstructions to be clearly marked; 
d) All steps, platforms and deck surface should be clear of any oil and / or grease residue; e) The decks must have unhindered access.

a) All crew must be trained and have a full understanding with regard to the launch / recovery of the rescue boat, including the release mechanism; 
b) Check and remove any obstructions i.e. under the rescue boat, in the water, on the boat deck; 
c) Slowly lower the rescue boat to reduce the impact on the water surface.

a) All crew must be trained and have a full understanding with regard to the launch / recovery of the rescue boat; 
b) Consult 'SOLAS Training Manual';
c) The on-load release hook is not to be used until the rescue boat is waterborne;
d) On recovery, ensure the on-load mechanism is reset and the hook is properly engaged.

a) All crew must be trained and have a full understanding with regard to the launch / recovery of rescue boat, including release mechanism; 
b) Consult 'SOLAS Training Manual'; 
c) Maintenance and inspections to be carried out in accordance with the Manufacturer's Manual and Company MPM system; 
d) All equipment i.e. lifting wires, hooks, davit, etc., must be visually inspected and condition checked regularly and prior to every use; 
e) Ensure the brake for remote launch has been disengaged.

a) Maintenance and inspections to be carried out in accordance with the Manufacturer's Manual and Company MPM system; 
b) The lifting wires should be visually inspected and condition checked regularly; 
c) Wires found in poor condition or damaged must be replaced immediately; 
d) The release hook, including safety latch and springs should be visually inspected and condition checked regularly; 
e) Ensure all lashing devices are removed prior to launching.

a) The vessel's course and speed are to be adjusted accordingly to minimise the effect of the weather conditions; 
b) In extreme weather, the launch / recovery of the rescue boat must be suspended until the weather improves; 
c) Training / drills involving the launch / recovery of the rescue boat is suspended with regard to the safety of the crew, until the weather improves.

a) All crew must be trained and have a full understanding with regard to the launch / recovery of the rescue boat; 
b) Use of suitable and appropriate PPE: overalls, safety shoes, hard hat, gloves, etc.; 
c) All crew involved in the rescue boat party must wear inflatable lifejackets, and were required, immersion suits; 
d) The crew should not be required to leave the protection of the vessel's safety rails - A life line or safety harness should be worn if there is any risk of falling; 
e) Adequate lighting to be provided; 
f) The vessel's speed must be reduced to less than 5 knots and, if possible, manoeuvred to create a lee to minimise the effects of the swell on the rescue boat.
